### Nullable Reference Types in C#

Nullable reference types (C# 8+) help prevent NullReferenceException by distinguishing between nullable and non-nullable reference types.

### Enabling Nullable Context

```csharp
// File-level enable
#nullable enable

// Project-level (in .csproj)
<Nullable>enable</Nullable>

// Disable selectively
#nullable disable
```

### Nullable vs Non-Nullable

```csharp
#nullable enable

string name = "Hello";       // Non-nullable (compiler ensures not null)
string? maybeNull = null;     // Nullable (may be null)

name = null;                  // Warning!
maybeNull = null;             // OK

Console.WriteLine(name.Length);   // OK
Console.WriteLine(maybeNull.Length);  // Warning! Possible null dereference
```

### Null Checking

```csharp
// Traditional null check
if (maybeNull != null)
    Console.WriteLine(maybeNull.Length);  // No warning

// Null-conditional operator
int? length = maybeNull?.Length;  // null if maybeNull is null

// Null-forgiving operator (!)
int len = maybeNull!.Length;  // Suppress warning (use carefully)

// Null coalescing
string result = maybeNull ?? "default";
```

### Nullable Annotations in APIs

```csharp
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; set; }        // Required, non-nullable
    public string? MiddleName { get; set; }  // Optional, nullable
    public int Age { get; set; }             // Value type
}
```

### Nullable Flow Analysis

The compiler tracks null state through code paths:

```csharp
string? text = GetValue();

if (text is null)
    return;

Console.WriteLine(text.Length);  // No warning - compiler knows not null here
```

### Nullable Warnings

| Warning | Meaning |
|---------|---------|
| CS8600 | Converting null literal to non-nullable type |
| CS8602 | Dereference of a possibly null reference |
| CS8603 | Possible null reference return |
| CS8618 | Non-nullable field not initialized |
| CS8625 | Cannot convert null literal to non-nullable type |

### Null-Friendly Operators

```csharp
// Null-conditional operator
int? count = list?.Count;
string? first = list?[0];

// Null coalescing
string display = name ?? "Guest";

// Null coalescing assignment
list ??= new List<string>();

// Null-forgiving operator
var result = GetValue()!;  // I know it's not null
```

### Generic Nullable

```csharp
public T? Find<T>(IEnumerable<T> source, Func<T, bool> predicate) where T : class
{
    return source.FirstOrDefault(predicate);
}
```

> **Key Point:** Nullable reference types add compile-time safety against null reference exceptions. Use `?` to mark nullable references. The compiler tracks null state through your code. Treat warnings as errors for best results. The null-forgiving operator `!` suppresses warnings but doesn't prevent runtime nulls.

### Migration from Legacy Code

```csharp
#nullable disable  // Legacy file
// Old code without nullable annotations

#nullable enable  // New code
string? maybe = GetValue();
```

### [MaybeNull] and [NotNull] Attributes

```csharp
public static bool TryParse(string? input, [MaybeNullWhen(false)] out int result)
{
    // Implementation
}

codeExample:
using System;

#nullable enable

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string? nullableMessage = GetNullMessage();
        string nonNullableMessage = GetMessage();

        // Safe access
        if (nullableMessage is not null)
            Console.WriteLine(nullableMessage.Length);

        Console.WriteLine(nonNullableMessage.Length);  // No warning
    }

    static string? GetNullMessage() => null;
    static string GetMessage() => "Hello!";
}

#nullable restore
